  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm a shy guy and don't know how to talk to strangers. How do I make new friends at college?",
  "response": "Making new friends as a shy person can feel intimidating, but college is a great place to meet people who share your interests. Here are some practical tips to help you step out of your comfort zone and build connections:\n\n### 1. **Start Small and Be Consistent**\n   - Smile and make eye contact with people in your classes or dorm. A simple \"hi\" or \"how\u2019s it going?\" can break the ice.\n   - Practice small talk about shared experiences, like class assignments or campus events.\n\n### 2. **Join Clubs or Organizations**\n   - Find groups that align with your hobbies or interests. This gives you a built-in topic to talk about and helps you meet like-minded people.\n   - Smaller clubs are often less overwhelming and easier to connect in.\n\n### 3. **Attend Social Events**\n   - Go to campus events, workshops, or mixers. Even if you\u2019re nervous, being around others can help you feel more comfortable over time.\n   - Start by attending events with a friend or roommate if possible.\n\n### 4. **Be Open in Class**\n   - Sit near the same people consistently and introduce yourself.\n   - Ask classmates about assignments or form study groups. Collaboration can lead to friendships.\n\n### 5. **Focus on Listening**\n   - If you\u2019re shy, let others do most of the talking. People appreciate good listeners.\n   - Ask questions about their interests or experiences to keep the conversation flowing.\n\n### 6. **Use Social Media or Apps**\n   - Join your college\u2019s Facebook groups, Discord servers, or other online communities. This can be an easier way to connect before meeting in person.\n   - Apps like Bumble BFF or Meetup can help you find people with similar interests.\n\n### 7. **Be Patient with Yourself**\n   - Building friendships takes time, and it\u2019s okay to take small steps.\n   - Remember, many people feel shy or nervous when meeting new people\u2014you\u2019re not alone.\n\n### 8. **Practice Self-Compassion**\n   - Don\u2019t pressure yourself to be the most outgoing person. Authenticity matters more than being the life of the party.\n   - Celebrate your progress, even if it\u2019s just saying hello to one new person.\n\n### 9. **Take Care of Yourself**\n   - Spend time doing things you enjoy to boost your confidence and reduce anxiety.\n   - Exercise, eat well, and get enough sleep to feel your best.\n\n### 10. **Be Approachable**\n   - Open body language (smiling, uncrossed arms) can make it easier for others to start conversations with you.\n   - Show kindness and positivity\u2014it\u2019s attractive to potential friends.\n\nRemember, making friends is a gradual process. Be kind to yourself, take small steps, and focus on building genuine connections. You\u2019ve got this! \ud83d\ude0a",
  "temperature": 1.0,
